                    "question_id": 26785354,
                    "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26785354/normalizing-a-list-of-numbers-in-python/26785729#26785729",
                    "body": "<p>How long is the list you're going to normalize?</p>\n\n<pre><code>def psum(it):\n    \"This function makes explicit how many calls to sum() are done.\"\n    print \"Another call!\"\n    return sum(it)\n\nraw = [0.07,0.14,0.07]\nprint \"How many calls to sum()?\"\nprint [ r/psum(raw) for r in raw]\n\nprint \"\\nAnd now?\"\ns = psum(raw)\nprint [ r/s for r in raw]\n\n# if one doesn't want auxiliary variables, it can be done inside\n# a list comprehension, but in my opinion it's quite Baroque    \nprint \"\\nAnd now?\"\nprint [ r/s  for s in [psum(raw)] for r in raw]\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><em>Output</em></p>\n\n<pre><code># How many calls to sum()?\n# Another call!\n# Another call!\n# Another call!\n# [0.25, 0.5, 0.25]\n# \n# And now?\n# Another call!\n# [0.25, 0.5, 0.25]\n# \n# And now?\n# Another call!\n# [0.25, 0.5, 0.25]\n</code></pre>\n"
                },
